As documented in [this blog][1] remove the `extends` and expose the `SecurityFilterChain`. 

```java
@EnableWebSecurity
static class HttpSecurityConfiguration {
    @public
    public SecurityFilterChain filterChain(HttpSecurity http) {
        http.authorizeRequests().anyRequest().authenticated();
        http.formLogin();
        http.httpBasic();
        http.sessionManagement().sessionCreationPolicy(SessionCreationPolicy.NEVER);
        http.csrf().disable();
        return http.build();
    }
}
```

Ideally you would rewrite the authorize part as well. 
```java
@EnableWebSecurity
static class HttpSecurityConfiguration {
    @public
    public SecurityFilterChain filterChain(HttpSecurity http) {
        http
        	.authorizeHttpRequests( (auth) -&gt; auth.anyRequest().authenticated())
        	.formLogin(Customizer.withDefaults())
        	.httpBasic(Customizer.withDefaults())
        	.sessionManagement(session -&gt; session.sessionCreationPolicy(SessionCreationPolicy.STATELESS))
        	.csrf().disable();
        return http.build();
    }
}
```


[1]: https://spring.io/blog/2022/02/21/spring-security-without-the-websecurityconfigureradapter

